  )}

  <!-- ═══ UPSIDE/DOWNSIDE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power:</strong> HCA routinely negotiates favorable reimbursement rates with insurers. Stronger-than-expected commercial rate increases directly boost margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Capacity Expansion:</strong> Expanding into high-growth markets like Florida and Texas can accelerate volume growth beyond the 6% assumption.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Allocation:</strong> Aggressive share buybacks reduce the share count, mechanically increasing intrinsic value per share over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Labor Costs:</strong> Nursing and clinical staff shortages remain structural. Escalating wage inflation can pressure margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> HCA operates with significant leverage. A sustained higher interest rate environment increases debt servicing costs, hurting FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Changes:</strong> Potential shifts in Medicare/Medicaid reimbursement policies or broader healthcare reform can negatively impact profitability.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a WACC of 8.5%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">HCA operates a capital-intensive business funded significantly by debt. A WACC blends the cost of equity (higher, due to equity risk premium) with the after-tax cost of debt (lower). An 8.5% discount rate balances the operational stability of hospitals against the high debt burden.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why assume only 6% FCF growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While revenue may grow consistently, hospitals are highly capital intensive. Maintaining and building new facilities requires substantial ongoing CapEx. We project a conservative 6% FCF growth to account for sustained capital reinvestment needs and potential labor cost pressures.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does debt affect this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Significantly. The DCF first calculates Enterprise Value (the value of the entire operations). We then must subtract Total Debt (and add cash) to find the Equity Value. Because HCA's debt is so large, a substantial portion of the Enterprise Value belongs to creditors, not shareholders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

